Learning Check 12.1

Go ahead and run a regression that models the log10-transformed prices as the outcome variable and uses log10-transformed square footage as the explanatory variable. Note that this is a basic regression (and not a multiple regression).

log_10_price_regression <- lm(log10_price ~ log10_size, data = house_prices)

get_regression_table(log_10_price_regression)

Learning Check 12.2

Use infer() to calculate a 95% confidence interval for the slope parameter in the previous regression.

bootstrap_dist_slope <- house_prices %>%
  specify(formula = log10_price ~ log10_size) %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") %>%
  calculate(stat = "slope")
bootstrap_dist_slope
## # A tibble: 1,000 x 2

Learning Check 12.3

Hypothesis tests around the slope. Use infer() to generate a hypothesis around the relationship between log10_price and log10_size. Visualize the resulting distribution and shade the p value associated with your observed statistic. What is the value of p?

null_distn_slope <- house_prices %>% 
  specify(log10_price ~ log10_size) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>% 
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "slope")
null_distn_slope
## # A tibble: 1,000 x 2
##    replicate      stat
##        <int>     <dbl>
##  1         1  0.00336 
##  2         2  0.00572 
##  3         3  0.00675 
##  4         4  0.00745 
##  5         5 -0.000597
##  6         6 -0.0218  
##  7         7 -0.00355 
##  8         8 -0.00345 
##  9         9  0.000271
## 10        10  0.00708 
## # ... with 990 more rows
visualize(null_distn_slope)+
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = get_regression_table(log_10_price_regression)$estimate[2], direction = "both")

null_distn_slope %>%
  get_p_value(obs_stat = get_regression_table(log_10_price_regression)$estimate[2], direction = "both")
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1       0

We have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship (thus a slope of zero) between the two variables because the p-value is 0, which is less than the 0.05 threshold set for the hypothesis test.

Learning Check 12.4

Go ahead and run a regression that models the log10-transformed prices as the outcome variable and uses log10-transformed square footage and condition as the explanatory variables. Note that this is a multiple regression (and not a basic regression).

Is it possible to use infer() for multiple regression?

multiple_regression_model <- lm(log10_price ~ log10_size*condition, data = house_prices)
get_regression_table(multiple_regression_model)

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(reg_points, aes(x = log10_price, y = residual))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "blue", size = 1)

It is possible to use infer for a multiple regression, so long as the multiple regression passes the LINE test. In this case, it is not possible because the multiple regression does not pass the E in the line test. The variance has a clear pattern trending upward from 5 - 6.5 and thus the infer package should not be used in this case.
